  "local_port": 55302,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best pancake recipe that doesn't use baking powder?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here's a delicious pancake recipe that doesn't require baking powder. Instead, it uses **buttermilk and baking soda** to achieve a tender and fluffy texture. If you don't have buttermilk on hand, you can make a substitute using regular milk and vinegar or lemon juice.\n\n### **Fluffy Buttermilk Pancakes (No Baking Powder)**\n\n#### **Ingredients:**\n- **1 1/2 cups (190g) all-purpose flour**\n- **2 tablespoons granulated sugar**\n- **1/2 teaspoon salt**\n- **1/2 teaspoon baking soda**\n- **1 1/4 cups (300ml) buttermilk**\n- **1 large egg**\n- **3 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted**\n- **1 teaspoon vanilla extract (optional)**\n- **Additional butter or oil for cooking**\n\n#### **Buttermilk Substitute (If Needed):**\nIf you don't have buttermilk, you can make 1 1/4 cups of substitutes by adding:\n- **1 tablespoon white vinegar or lemon juice** to a measuring cup\n- **Fill with milk to reach 1 1/4 cups**\n- **Stir and let it sit for 5 minutes** before using\n\n#### **Instructions:**\n\n1. **Prepare the Dry Ingredients:**\n   - In a large mixing bowl, whisk together the **all-purpose flour**, **granulated sugar**, **salt**, and **baking soda**. Ensure they are well combined to distribute the baking soda evenly.\n\n2. **Combine the Wet Ingredients:**\n   - In another bowl or a large measuring cup, **whisk together the buttermilk**, **egg**, **melted butter**, and **vanilla extract** (if using) until smooth.\n\n3. **Mix the Batter:**\n   - Pour the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients. **Stir gently** with a spatula or whisk until just combined. It's okay if the batter is slightly lumpy; overmixing can make the pancakes tough.\n\n4. **Preheat the Griddle or Pan:**\n   - Heat a non-stick skillet or griddle over **medium heat**. To test if it's hot enough, sprinkle a few drops of water on the surface. If they dance and evaporate quickly, the pan is ready.\n   - Lightly **grease the surface** with butter or oil using a paper towel or brush.\n\n5. **Cook the Pancakes:**\n   - For each pancake, pour about **1/4 cup** of batter onto the skillet.\n   - **Cook until bubbles form** on the surface and the edges look set, approximately **2-3 minutes**.\n   - Carefully flip the pancake using a spatula and cook for another **1-2 minutes** on the other side, until golden brown.\n   - Adjust the heat as necessary to prevent burning.\n\n6. **Serve Warm:**\n   - Transfer the cooked pancakes to a plate and **keep warm** in a low oven if cooking in batches.\n   - Serve with your favorite toppings such as **maple syrup**, **fresh berries**, **whipped cream**, or **butter**.\n\n#### **Tips for Perfect Pancakes Without Baking Powder:**\n\n- **Use Fresh Baking Soda:** Ensure your baking soda is fresh to provide the necessary leavening. You can test it by adding a small amount to vinegar\u2014it should fizz vigorously.\n  \n- **Don't Overmix the Batter:** Mix until the ingredients are just combined. Overmixing can develop the gluten in the flour, resulting in denser pancakes.\n  \n- **Proper Heat Control:** Medium heat is ideal. Too hot, and the pancakes will burn on the outside while remaining raw inside. Adjust the heat as needed while cooking.\n  \n- **Let the Batter Rest:** Allowing the batter to rest for about 5-10 minutes before cooking can help the baking soda react better with the buttermilk, leading to fluffier pancakes.\n\nEnjoy your homemade, fluffy pancakes without the need for baking powder!",
